performance_optimizations.description:
The join_aggregation phase (104.0ms) performs ~3-4M iterations of date filtering, hash lookups, and revenue calculations. Several operations are SIMD-friendly:

1. Date filtering (l_shipdate > date_1995_03_15): Vectorize using AVX2 to process 8 int32 comparisons per instruction
2. Revenue calculation (l_extendedprice * (1.0 - l_discount)): Vectorize using AVX2 to process 4 doubles per instruction

Specific changes to q3.cpp:
1. Add #include <immintrin.h> for AVX2 intrinsics
2. In the lineitem scan loop (lines 350-377), replace scalar processing with batched SIMD:

```cpp
const __m256i date_threshold = _mm256_set1_epi32(date_1995_03_15);
const __m256d ones = _mm256_set1_pd(1.0);

for (size_t i = start; i + 8 <= end; i += 8) {
    // SIMD date comparison
    __m256i shipdates = _mm256_loadu_si256((__m256i*)(l_shipdate + i));
    __m256i date_mask = _mm256_cmpgt_epi32(shipdates, date_threshold);
    int mask = _mm256_movemask_epi8(date_mask);
    if (mask == 0) continue; // All 8 rows filtered out

    // Process matching rows (scalar hash lookup, SIMD revenue calc)
    for (int lane = 0; lane < 8; ++lane) {
        if ((mask >> (lane * 4)) & 0xF) {
            auto it = qualified_orders.find(l_orderkey[i + lane]);
            if (it != qualified_orders.end()) {
                // SIMD revenue: load 4 prices and 4 discounts, compute revenues
                // (Requires gathering matching indices or hybrid approach)
                double revenue = l_extendedprice[i + lane] * (1.0 - l_discount[i + lane]);
                AggregateKey key{l_orderkey[i + lane], it->second.first, it->second.second};
                local_map[key].revenue += revenue;
            }
        }
    }
}
// Scalar tail for remaining rows
```

Note: SIMD revenue calculation is complex due to data dependencies (only matching rows). Alternative: Use branch-free masking or gather/scatter instructions (AVX512).

Expected improvement: Date filtering is ~5-10% of join_aggregation time (~5-10ms), SIMD reduces by 6-8x → saves 4-9ms. Revenue calculation is ~10-15% (~10-15ms), SIMD reduces by 3-4x → saves 7-12ms. Total savings: 11-21ms. Reference: parallelism/simd.md.

Challenges: SIMD arithmetic requires careful handling of sparse matching (low density after filters). Hybrid approach may be needed.

The merge phase (46.3ms, 6.4% of total) sequentially combines local aggregation maps from 64 threads. With ~1000-5000 groups per thread, this involves ~64K-320K hash operations performed single-threaded.

Specific changes to q3.cpp:
1. Replace sequential merge (lines 391-403) with parallel tree reduction
2. Use log2(num_threads) merge levels, parallelizing each level
3. Pattern:
```cpp
std::vector<absl::flat_hash_map<AggregateKey, AggregateValue>> current = std::move(local_maps);
while (current.size() > 1) {
    std::vector<absl::flat_hash_map<AggregateKey, AggregateValue>> next((current.size() + 1) / 2);
    std::vector<std::thread> merge_threads;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < next.size(); ++i) {
        merge_threads.emplace_back([&, i]() {
            next[i] = std::move(current[i * 2]);
            if (i * 2 + 1 < current.size()) {
                for (auto& [key, val] : current[i * 2 + 1]) {
                    next[i][key].revenue += val.revenue;
                }
            }
        });
    }
    for (auto& t : merge_threads) t.join();
    current = std::move(next);
}
global_map = std::move(current[0]);
```

Expected improvement: Current 46.3ms single-threaded → ~8-12ms with parallel reduction (4-6x speedup). Savings: 34-38ms. Reference: aggregation/partial-aggregation.md recommends parallel merge for multi-threaded aggregation.

Current code identifies qualifying blocks via zone maps, then scans them in parallel across threads. On HDD, this can cause seeks if threads access non-contiguous blocks. Better approach: process qualifying blocks in sequential file order, distributing work to threads via a work queue.

Specific changes to q3.cpp:
1. After identifying qualifying_blocks (line 227), SORT them by block_id to ensure sequential file order
2. Change thread processing pattern from strided access (idx += num_threads) to sequential block assignment:
```cpp
std::atomic<size_t> next_block_idx{0};
for (size_t t = 0; t < num_threads; ++t) {
    order_threads.emplace_back([&]() {
        while (true) {
            size_t idx = next_block_idx.fetch_add(1);
            if (idx >= qualifying_blocks.size()) break;
            size_t block_id = qualifying_blocks[idx];
            // Process block...
        }
    });
}
```
3. Apply same pattern to lineitem scan (lines 339-379)

Benefits: Sequential block processing reduces HDD seeks. Threads dynamically grab next block, ensuring no idle threads. Load balancing is automatic.

Expected improvement: On HDD with current strided access, threads may cause ~10-20 random seeks per second. Sequential access reduces seeks by 50-70%. Estimate: 20-40ms savings on orders scan. Reference: storage/persistent-storage.md recommends sequential access patterns for HDD.
